25|$|The most {{effective}} strategy predators use against schooling fish is first to scare them <b>into</b> forming <b>a</b> bait <b>ball.</b> Strategies {{such as those}} outlined {{in the previous section}} can work to a degree against freely streaming fish schools, but work much better if the fish school is first compacted <b>into</b> <b>a</b> bait <b>ball.</b> It is difficult for predators working individually to scare <b>a</b> fish school <b>into</b> <b>a</b> bait <b>ball,</b> <b>and</b> they usually work together.|$|R
